          Step 5.  Preparing the Working-copy Diskettes          Step 5.  Preparing the Working-copy Diskettes

          Customers who plan  to install the software onto a  hard disk may
          skip this step.   Customers who plan to install the software onto
          a Waterloo JANET network fileserver may also skip this step.

          If you have a diskette-only system,   you should create a working
          copy of  the diskette.   This will  be the diskette that  you use
          from day to day.

          (1) To install  the WATCOM software  onto one or  more diskettes,
              make  sure that  each  target  diskette has  been  formatted.
              Simple  instructions  for  formatting a  diskette  are  given
              below.   More detailed instructions can  be found in your DOS
              manual.

          (2) Never format a  diskette which contains information  that you
              wish to keep.   The formatting process erases any information
              which might have been on the diskette  so it is best to start
              with a new, unused diskette.

          (3) To format your diskette, place a copy of your DOS diskette in
              drive "A" and  enter a DOS "FORMAT" command  of the following
              form:

                 A>format b:

              Remove  the DOS  diskette from  drive  "A" and  place a  new,
              unused diskette in  drive "B".   If you do not  have a second
              diskette drive,  simply place the diskette into the "A" drive
              (the FORMAT  program will treat drive  "A" as though  it were
              drive "B").  Proceed as instructed by the FORMAT program.

          (4) Format  as many  diskettes as  required.    We recommend  one
              diskette for each diskette in the WATCOM package.


          Step 6.  Preparing Waterloo JANET Minidisks          Step 6.  Preparing Waterloo JANET Minidisks

          Customers who do not plan to install the software onto a Waterloo
          JANET network fileserver may skip this step.

          Before proceeding  with the Waterloo JANET  minidisk preparation,
          we recommend that  you familiarize yourself with  the contents of
              ________  _____ ____________ _____          the Waterloo  JANET Installation Guide.    Use it as  a reference
          guide for this step.

          (1) To install  the WATCOM software  onto a JANET  minidisk,  you
              must first create a minidisk.    Log on to the administrators
              account from any workstation.    Use the JANET Administrative
              (Directory)   Maintenance program  "JAM" to  create a  userid
              called EDIT and make this user's minidisk 320K bytes in size.
              The minidisk mode should be set for "public read".
          4                                              WATCOM Editor V3.5


 
          (2) Insert  your WATCOM  Editor Software  diskette  into the  "A"
              drive  of  the network  controller/fileserver.    Access  the
              controller's diskette drive as the virtual "C" disk by typing
              the command:

                 A:ACCESS C:FLPYA rdpswd

              where  "rdpswd"  is  the  current  "read"  password  for  the
              diskette  drive.    If  you  do not  know  the  password  for
              accessing the controller's  diskette drive,  you may  use the
              Waterloo JANET "JAM" program to find out this information.

          (3) Access  the  EDIT minidisk  that  you  created above  as  the
              virtual "D" disk by typing the command:

                 A:ACCESS D:EDIT wtpswd

              where  "wtpswd"  is  the  current  "write"  password.    This
              password was specified when you created the minidisk.

          (4) You  are now  ready for  the  next step  in the  installation
              procedure.   In the following step,  the source diskette will
              be the  "C" drive  and the  output location  will be  the "D"
              drive.


          Step 7.  Run the INSTALL Program          Step 7.  Run the INSTALL Program

          Before starting this step,  you should ensure that the computer's
          date and time have been correctly set by using the DOS "DATE" and
          "TIME" commands.

          The installation  procedure will  copy several  files,  including
          those that are not absolutely required to run the software,  from
          the source diskette to the specified destination.  If, because of
          space limitations,  you wish to copy only a subset of these files
          then  you should  perform a  manual  software installation.    To
          manually install the software, use the DOS "COPY" command to copy
          necessary and desired files to the  target diskette or hard disk.
          Section 4,  entitled "Diskette  Contents",  describes which files
          are necessary to run the software.

          When running  the INSTALL  batch program,   you must  specify two
          parameters.

             INSTALL  source-diskette:  output-location

          The first parameter designates the diskette drive containing your
          backup copy  of the WATCOM source  diskette.   The colon  must be
          specified  after   the  drive  letter.    The   second  parameter
          designates  the location  where  the  WATCOM software  should  be
          placed.   This location would be the drive designation (e.g., B:,
          C:, D:, etc.)  and, optionally,  a directory specification of the
          disk or diskette that is to receive the files.  When specifying a
                     ___ ____ _______ ___ ________ _____          directory, you must include the trailing slash.
